{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> Ὑάκινθος</b> [ῠᾰ], ὁ, <br /> <b>Hyacinthus,</b> a Laconian youth, beloved by Apollo, who killed him by an unlucky cast of the discus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 1469 (Lyric poetry), 2nd c.AD: Apollodorus Damascenus Mechanicus 3.10.3, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 3.1.3: compare Ὑακίνθια. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> as <i>appellative</i>, <br /><Level2><b>__B.I</b></Level2> <b>ὑάκινθος</b>, ὁ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.348, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 1.35.4 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; but ἡ in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 94, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 6.8.2, 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus, etc. (see. below)\">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>wild hyacinth, bluebell, Scilla bifolia,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” [same place], “hymnus ad Cererem” 7, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 6.8.1, 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 4.62. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.I.2</b></Level3> <b>blue larkspur, Delphinium Ajacis,</b> ὑ. σπαρτή [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 6.8.2 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; said to have sprung up from the blood of Hyacinthus or (<i>accusative</i> to others) of Telamonian Ajax: and the ancients thought they could decipher on the petals the initial letters AI, or the interj. AIAI,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 2nd c.BC: Moschus Bucolicus 3.6 \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]; hence the epithets γραπτά [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 10.28; αἰαστής 2nd c.BC: Nicander Epicus “fragment” 74.31; πολύθρηνος [prev. author] “Th.” 902; πολύκλαυτος “IG” 14.607; cf. Pseudo-Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 3.73. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.I.3</b></Level3> ὑ. πορφυρέη, probably <b>Lilium Martagon,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Euphorio Epicus 40, “Anthologia Graeca” 5.146 (1st c.BC: Meleager Epigrammaticus). \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.II</b></Level2> ὑάκινθος, ἡ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Heliodorus Scriptor Eroticus, ὁ 1st c.AD: Philo Judaeus and 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]:—a precious stone, of blue colour [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"(1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 3.7.7)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>], perhaps <b>aquamarine,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Rev. 21.20, “Periplus Maris Rubri [1st c.AD]” 56, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Syr.D.” 32, 3rd c.AD: Heliodorus Scriptor Eroticus 2.30, “Codex Justinianus [4th-6th c.AD]” 11.12.1, etc.; compare 1st c.AD: Plinius Rerum Naturalium Scriptor “Historia Naturalis” 37.125. \">NT+1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.III</b></Level2> name of a <b>blue</b> colour, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Antiquitates Judaicae” 3.6.1, “PHolm.” 17.3 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; <b>blue stuff,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Exo.28.8, 1st c.AD: Philo Judaeus 2.148, 1st c.AD: Josephus Historicus “Bellum Judaicum” 5.5.4; χιτώνια τὴν χροιὰν ὑακίνθου 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Tactica” 34.6. \">LXX+1st c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5192","accentedUnicode":"ὑάκινθος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5191","matchingForm":"ὑακίνθινος","stepTransliteration":"huakinthinos","gloss":"dark blue","_zh_tw_Gloss":"紫瑪瑙","_es_Gloss":"azul oscuro","_zh_Gloss":"紫玛瑙"}],"shortDef":"jacinth","mediumDef":"jacinth <br /><b>a hyacinth,</b> a gem resembling the color of the <b>hyacinth flower, dark blue,</b> <ref='Rev.21.20'>Rev. 21:20</ref>*","stepGloss":"hyacinth","stepTransliteration":"huakinthos","count":1,"_es_Definition":"jacinto (una piedra preciosa, quizá de color 